1
00:00:13,098 --> 00:00:14,477
"Look at me!"

2
00:00:16,496 --> 00:00:21,121
That phrase turned me
into an eye-contact coach.

3
00:00:22,615 --> 00:00:25,559
I'm the mother of Ivan; he's 15 years old.

4
00:00:26,339 --> 00:00:28,283
Ivan has autism,

5
00:00:28,307 --> 00:00:29,852
he doesn't speak,

6
00:00:29,876 --> 00:00:31,866
and he communicates through an iPad,

7
00:00:31,890 --> 00:00:35,762
where his whole universe of words
exists in images.

8
00:00:37,767 --> 00:00:42,309
He was diagnosed
when he was two and a half.

9
00:00:43,527 --> 00:00:47,540
I still remember that day painfully.

10
00:00:49,299 --> 00:00:52,032
My husband and I felt really lost;

11
00:00:53,309 --> 00:00:55,487
we didn't know where to begin.

12
00:00:56,760 --> 00:00:59,185
There was no internet,

13
00:00:59,209 --> 00:01:01,639
you couldn't Google information,

14
00:01:02,525 --> 00:01:04,502
so we made those first steps

15
00:01:05,439 --> 00:01:07,565
out of sheer intuition.

16
00:01:09,669 --> 00:01:11,759
Ivan would not maintain eye contact,

17
00:01:12,831 --> 00:01:15,080
he had lost the words that he did know,

18
00:01:16,104 --> 00:01:20,081
and he didn't respond to his name
or to anything we asked him,

19
00:01:20,889 --> 00:01:23,176
as if words were noise.

20
00:01:25,287 --> 00:01:29,195
The only way I could know

21
00:01:29,837 --> 00:01:31,455
what was going on with him,

22
00:01:32,123 --> 00:01:33,622
what he felt,

23
00:01:34,157 --> 00:01:36,016
was looking him in the eye.

24
00:01:37,629 --> 00:01:39,782
But that bridge was broken.

25
00:01:42,441 --> 00:01:44,872
How could I teach him about life?

26
00:01:47,339 --> 00:01:51,247
When I did things he liked,
he would look at me,

27
00:01:51,271 --> 00:01:52,805
and we were connected.

28
00:01:53,705 --> 00:01:57,273
So I dedicated myself
to working with him on those things,

29
00:01:57,297 --> 00:02:01,626
so we would have more and more
eye-contact moments.

30
00:02:03,110 --> 00:02:09,631
We would spend hours and hours playing tag
with his older sister, Alexia,

31
00:02:10,322 --> 00:02:12,939
and when we said: "I caught you!"

32
00:02:14,006 --> 00:02:15,700
he would look around for us,

33
00:02:16,790 --> 00:02:21,529
and at that moment,
I could feel he was alive.

34
00:02:24,908 --> 00:02:29,835
We also hold a record for hours spent
in a swimming pool.

35
00:02:31,002 --> 00:02:34,358
Ivan always had a passion for water.

36
00:02:35,654 --> 00:02:38,511
I remember when he was two and a half,

37
00:02:39,581 --> 00:02:42,881
on a rainy winter day,

38
00:02:42,905 --> 00:02:45,381
I was taking him to an indoor pool,

39
00:02:45,405 --> 00:02:48,055
because even on rainy days
we'd go swimming.

40
00:02:49,643 --> 00:02:53,331
We were on the highway,
and I took the wrong exit.

41
00:02:54,115 --> 00:02:58,057
He burst into tears and cried
inconsolably, nonstop,

42
00:02:58,081 --> 00:02:59,601
until I turned back.

43
00:03:00,356 --> 00:03:01,978
Only then did he calm down.

44
00:03:03,348 --> 00:03:07,044
How was it possible
that a two and a half year old

45
00:03:07,068 --> 00:03:08,875
didn't respond to his own name,

46
00:03:09,671 --> 00:03:13,795
yet in the middle of the rain and fog,
where I couldn't see anything,

47
00:03:13,819 --> 00:03:18,125
he knew the exact route?

48
00:03:20,886 --> 00:03:24,326
That's when I realized that Ivan
had an exceptional visual memory,

49
00:03:25,362 --> 00:03:28,762
and that that would be my way in.

50
00:03:29,647 --> 00:03:32,017
So I started taking
pictures of everything,

51
00:03:32,688 --> 00:03:34,834
and teaching him what life was like,

52
00:03:34,858 --> 00:03:38,448
showing it to him, picture by picture.

53
00:03:39,578 --> 00:03:44,276
Even now, it's the way Ivan communicates

54
00:03:44,300 --> 00:03:45,662
what he wants,

55
00:03:46,131 --> 00:03:47,410
what he needs

56
00:03:48,212 --> 00:03:50,602
and also what he feels.

57
00:03:53,843 --> 00:03:57,042
But it wasn't just
Ivan's eye contact that mattered.

58
00:03:58,752 --> 00:04:00,716
Everyone else's did, too.

59
00:04:02,555 --> 00:04:06,545
How could I make people see
not only his autism,

60
00:04:06,569 --> 00:04:07,965
but see him the person

61
00:04:09,132 --> 00:04:10,801
and everything he can give;

62
00:04:12,136 --> 00:04:13,882
everything he can do;

63
00:04:15,207 --> 00:04:17,845
the things he likes and doesn't like,

64
00:04:17,869 --> 00:04:19,709
just like any one of us?

65
00:04:21,131 --> 00:04:24,201
But for that, I also had
to give of myself.

66
00:04:25,614 --> 00:04:27,661
I had to have the strength to let him go,

67
00:04:28,716 --> 00:04:30,775
which was extremely difficult.

68
00:04:33,117 --> 00:04:34,587
Ivan was 11 years old,

69
00:04:35,575 --> 00:04:39,265
and he went for treatment
in a neighborhood near our house.

70
00:04:40,613 --> 00:04:44,044
One afternoon,
while I was waiting for him,

71
00:04:44,683 --> 00:04:46,019
I went into a greengrocer,

72
00:04:46,043 --> 00:04:49,312
a typical neighborhood store
with a little bit of everything.

73
00:04:50,248 --> 00:04:51,800
While doing the shopping,

74
00:04:51,824 --> 00:04:55,034
I started talking to Jose, the owner.

75
00:04:56,762 --> 00:04:58,145
I told him about Ivan,

76
00:04:58,877 --> 00:05:00,233
that he had autism,

77
00:05:01,257 --> 00:05:05,525
and that I wanted him to learn
to walk down the street by himself,

78
00:05:05,549 --> 00:05:07,649
without anyone holding his hand.

79
00:05:08,695 --> 00:05:12,361
So I decided to ask Jose
if Thursdays around 2pm,

80
00:05:13,329 --> 00:05:17,078
Ivan could come and help him arrange
the water bottles on the shelves,

81
00:05:17,102 --> 00:05:19,417
because he loved to organize things.

82
00:05:19,441 --> 00:05:23,207
And as a reward, he could buy
some chocolate cookies,

83
00:05:23,231 --> 00:05:24,977
which were his favorite.

84
00:05:27,663 --> 00:05:29,163
He said "yes" right away.

85
00:05:30,635 --> 00:05:33,877
So that's how it went for a year:

86
00:05:33,901 --> 00:05:36,191
Ivan would go to Jose's greengrocer,

87
00:05:37,132 --> 00:05:40,576
help him arrange the shelves
of water bottles

88
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:45,863
with the labels perfectly
lined up on the same side,

89
00:05:45,887 --> 00:05:49,494
and he would leave happy
with his chocolate cookies.

90
00:05:55,874 --> 00:05:58,294
Jose is not an expert in autism.

91
00:06:01,111 --> 00:06:03,922
There is no need to be an expert

92
00:06:05,032 --> 00:06:08,820
nor do anything heroic to include someone.

93
00:06:11,904 --> 00:06:13,900
We just need to be there --

94
00:06:14,335 --> 00:06:15,907
(Applause)

95
00:06:22,762 --> 00:06:24,334
(Applause ends)

96
00:06:25,557 --> 00:06:27,074
Really, no heroic deed --

97
00:06:28,797 --> 00:06:31,089
we simply need to be close.

98
00:06:33,768 --> 00:06:35,444
And if we are afraid of something

99
00:06:36,331 --> 00:06:38,515
or we don't understand something,

100
00:06:38,539 --> 00:06:39,788
we need to ask.

101
00:06:41,002 --> 00:06:42,682
Let's be curious

102
00:06:44,182 --> 00:06:47,342
but never indifferent.

103
00:06:50,037 --> 00:06:53,587
Let's have the courage
to look each other in the eye,

104
00:06:56,206 --> 00:06:58,308
because by looking,

105
00:06:58,332 --> 00:07:01,405
we can open a whole world to someone else.

106
00:07:02,962 --> 00:07:05,360
(Applause)

107
00:07:05,384 --> 00:07:07,708
(Cheers)